President Obama has named nineteen recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the highest civilian honor in the United States. The award is given to individuals who have made significant contributions to the country in areas such as national security, world peace, and cultural or public endeavors. The recipients include choreographer Alvin Ailey, author Isabel Allende, journalist Tom Brokaw, civil rights activists James Chaney, Andrew Goodman, and Michael Schwerner, physicist Mildred Dresselhaus, Congressman John Dingell, human rights advocate Ethel Kennedy, Native American activist Suzan Harjo, public servant Abner Mikva, Congresswoman Patsy Takemoto Mink, Congressman Edward Roybal, golfer Charles Sifford, economist Robert Solow, theater composer Stephen Sondheim, actress Meryl Streep, actress and social activist Marlo Thomas, singer-songwriter Stevie Wonder, and journalist and television host Tom Brokaw. The awards will be presented at the White House on November 24th.